<item>
            <title>[SPARK-41379] Inconsistency of spark session in DataFrame in user function for foreachBatch sink in PySpark</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-41379</link>
                <project id="12315420" key="SPARK">Spark</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://docs.databricks.com/_static/notebooks/merge-in-streaming.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://docs.databricks.com/_static/notebooks/merge-in-streaming.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;According to some manual testing against above code example in PySpark, it seems like the property of sparkSession in given DataFrame is not the same with cloned session in streaming query. In other words, &lt;tt&gt;df.sparkSession&lt;/tt&gt; does not seem to be same with the cloned spark session which you can access via &lt;tt&gt;df._jdf.sparkSession()&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So which session to pick depends on the actual implementation of method in PySpark DataFrame, which users would never know. If it leads to pick the different session than expected, it leads to open backdoor for avoiding restrictions (e.g. AQE), unable to see session scoped resources (e.g. temp view), etc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So it&#8217;s quite critical to sync two sessions to refer the same.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
